    <section class="methodology card">
      <h2>Our Methodology</h2>
      <p>Identifying the best vehicles for copper exposure requires a nuanced evaluation of both commodity dynamics and corporate fundamentals. Our ranking system for 2025 and 2026 relies on the following key metrics:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Exposure Purity:</strong> We assess how closely an ETF or stock is tied to copper revenue versus other base metals (like zinc or iron ore) to ensure investors are actually getting the thesis they are buying.</li>
        <li><strong>Operational Leverage vs. Spot Correlation:</strong> We balance funds that provide high operational leverage (miners that expand margins as prices rise) against those that offer direct, low-tracking-error exposure to spot futures.</li>
        <li><strong>Geopolitical Risk Profile:</strong> For mining equities and the ETFs that hold them, we evaluate the jurisdictional stability of their primary assets, penalizing concentrated exposure in politically volatile regions.</li>
        <li><strong>Cost Efficiency:</strong> For ETFs, we prioritize low expense ratios and minimal contango drag (the cost of rolling futures contracts). For miners, we focus on first-quartile All-In Sustaining Costs (AISC).</li>
        <li><strong>Capital Return:</strong> We reward funds and companies with a track record of returning capital to shareholders via sustainable dividend yields and share repurchases.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This comprehensive framework ensures that our recommendations are resilient across various phases of the commodity cycle.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Why invest in copper ETFs for 2026?</summary>
        <p>Copper is essential for electric vehicles, renewable energy infrastructure, and grid modernization. A looming supply deficit relative to this surging demand makes it a compelling investment theme for 2026.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between a copper miners ETF and a physical copper ETF?</summary>
        <p>Miners ETFs hold stocks of companies that extract copper, offering potential dividends and operational leverage. Physical/futures ETFs track the spot price of the commodity itself.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do copper ETFs pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>ETFs holding copper mining stocks often pay dividends derived from the underlying companies' profits. However, ETFs tracking physical copper or futures generally do not offer significant yields.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the risks of investing in copper?</summary>
        <p>Copper prices are highly sensitive to global economic health. A recession or slowdown in industrial activity, particularly in major economies like China, can cause sharp declines.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does the EV transition affect copper demand?</summary>
        <p>Electric vehicles require significantly more copper than traditional combustion engine vehicles, from the batteries to the motors, drastically increasing long-term structural demand.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
